A righteous man in 2026 is not a “good Christian boy” with a cleaner playlist.

He is a man who has been made right with God through Christ, and then spends the rest of his life making war on everything in him that does not belong to Christ. That matters because you cannot grindset your way into righteousness. You do not become righteous because you lift, make money, attract women, quit porn for three weeks, or become more “masculine.” Romans says righteousness comes through faith in Jesus Christ, not through your résumé, and 2 Corinthians says Christ took sin so we could become right with God in him. Start there, or you will turn manhood into another idol.  ￼

But once Christ gets hold of a man, that man starts walking differently.

A righteous man is under authority.

The first mark of a righteous man is not confidence. It is submission.

Not weak submission. Not passive submission. I mean he knows he is not God.

Psalm 1 describes the righteous man as someone who refuses the counsel of the wicked and feeds his mind on God’s instruction. In plain English: he does not let idiots disciple him. In 2026, “the counsel of the wicked” is not just some villain in a robe. It is your feed. It is your group chat. It is porn logic. It is hustle-bro greed. It is bitter men online telling you women are the enemy. It is soft men telling you discipline is toxic. A righteous man asks, “Who is forming me?” and then he cuts off the voices that are making him less like Christ.  ￼

On a Tuesday afternoon, that looks like this: you do not open your phone before you open your Bible. You do not let TikTok set your desires before God sets your mind. You do not call it “just entertainment” when it is training your heart to envy, lust, mock, or rage.

A righteous man carries himself with integrity.

Proverbs says the righteous man “walks in his integrity.” That means there is not a church version of you, a gym version of you, a girl-you-like version of you, and a late-night-private-browser version of you. Integrity means the pieces are joined together. You are one man.  ￼

So he tells the truth. He pays what he owes. He shows up when he said he would. He does not exaggerate his income, fake his spiritual life, manipulate women with attention, or act broke when it is time to be generous but rich when it is time to impress people.

This is grown-man stuff: your word should become boringly reliable.

Not flashy. Reliable.

A righteous man kills lust. He does not negotiate with it.

Let’s get direct.

Jesus does not treat lust like a harmless private habit. He says the man who looks with lustful intent has already dragged adultery into his heart. Then he uses violent language about cutting off what causes sin. He is not telling you to mutilate yourself. He is telling you to stop treating soul-destroying sin like a pet you can train.  ￼

Paul says God’s will is your sanctification, including that you abstain from sexual immorality and learn to control your own body in holiness and honor. That is not vague. God expects you to rule your body instead of being ruled by your urges.  ￼

So, no, porn is not “just a struggle.” It is a teacher. It teaches you to use women without loving them. It teaches you to want pleasure without covenant. It trains you to be passive, hidden, entitled, and weak. A righteous man does not make peace with that.

What does he do?

He removes access. He confesses to a real man, not just to himself in his journal. He stops pretending “I’ll just try harder” is a plan. James says confession and prayer belong together because healing is not meant to happen in secrecy.  ￼

That means blockers, accountability, deleting apps, moving the phone out of the bedroom, not being alone with the internet at midnight, and telling one trusted older man the truth: “I’m not okay. I need help killing this.”

Not because you are uniquely disgusting.

Because you are at war.

Colossians does not say “manage” sexual sin. It says put it to death.  ￼

A righteous man is disciplined, not lazy.

The Bible has no patience for a man who keeps making excuses for laziness.

Proverbs tells the sluggard to learn from the ant: it prepares, gathers, works ahead, and does not need someone standing over it every hour to make it move. Then Proverbs warns that “a little” extra sleep and “a little” folding of the hands can end in poverty coming like an armed man. The point is not that rest is evil. The point is that comfort becomes dangerous when it becomes your master.  ￼

So yes, go to the gym. Good. Train your body.

But do not be the guy who can deadlift heavy and cannot get out of bed to pray. Do not be the guy with visible abs and invisible character. Do not be disciplined with protein and sloppy with lust. Do not build your body while your soul gets soft.

A righteous man does hard things because God gave him strength to spend, not admire.

He works. He learns. He saves. He cleans his room. He keeps his body under control. He does the unsexy things that make him useful.

A righteous man uses strength to serve, not dominate.

This is where both modern lies fall apart.

One lie says manhood is domination: get power, get money, get women, never apologize, never be vulnerable, crush everyone.

The other lie says manhood is basically being harmless: never confront, never lead, never risk, never make anyone uncomfortable.

Jesus rejects both.

He says worldly rulers lord power over people, but his men are different: greatness is service, and the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve and give his life. That means biblical leadership is not “I’m the king, obey me.” It is “I go first in sacrifice.”  ￼

If you want a wife, learn this now: leadership is not getting a woman to orbit your ego. Ephesians tells husbands to love their wives as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her. That is the model. Not control. Not passivity. Sacrifice. Protection. Nourishment. Responsibility.  ￼

On a Tuesday, that looks like apologizing first when you are wrong. It looks like making decisions instead of drifting. It looks like refusing to flirt with women you have no intention of honoring. It looks like becoming the kind of man whose future wife does not have to mother him.

A righteous man is strong and loving at the same time.

Paul says, “Be watchful, stand firm… act like men… be strong,” and then immediately says everything should be done in love. That combination matters. Strength without love becomes cruelty. Love without strength becomes cowardice. A righteous man refuses both.  ￼

So he can be gentle without being soft.

He can be kind without being fake.

He can confront without being a jerk.

He can lose an argument without losing his mind.

He can be misunderstood without spiraling.

He can take correction without acting like a child.

Galatians describes the fruit of the Spirit as love, patience, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control. That means the Holy Spirit does not produce a man who is ruled by rage, lust, insecurity, or impulse. He produces a man with reins on his strength.  ￼

Self-control is masculine. Gentleness is masculine. Faithfulness is masculine. Not because Instagram says so. Because God says so.

A righteous man refuses the wrong chase.

Paul tells Timothy, “flee” certain things and “pursue” righteousness, godliness, faith, love, steadfastness, and gentleness. Notice that: a man of God is not just known by what he avoids. He is known by what he chases.  ￼

So what does he refuse?

He refuses porn.

He refuses bitterness.

He refuses laziness dressed up as “rest.”

He refuses career idolatry.

He refuses using women for validation.

He refuses being discipled by angry men online.

He refuses fake humility that is really fear.

He refuses to be a victim of his childhood, his temptations, his singleness, or his generation.

And what does he chase?

He chases holiness.

He chases wisdom.

He chases skill.

He chases brotherhood with serious men.

He chases financial steadiness, not so he can flex, but so he can provide and give.

He chases a clean conscience.

He chases the kind of life where his future children, if God gives him children, are blessed by his integrity before they ever hear his advice.

A righteous man walks humbly.

Micah gives one of the simplest summaries in the Bible: do justice, love kindness, and walk humbly with God. That is not soft. That is sturdy.  ￼

Do justice: do what is right even when it costs you.

Love kindness: do not become a hard, cynical man who excuses cruelty as “truth.”

Walk humbly: remember you are not self-made. You are not the main character. You are dust with breath in your lungs because God is patient.

A righteous man can look another man in the eye. He can also get on his knees.

That is the balance.

So what does this look like Monday through Sunday?

It looks like waking up and seeking God before the algorithm gets a vote.

It looks like going to work even when you are tired, doing the job well, and not needing applause for basic faithfulness.

It looks like training your body but not worshiping it.

It looks like having a budget.

It looks like being in a real church, not just consuming sermons online.

It looks like one or two older men knowing the truth about your life.

It looks like dating with clarity: “I am getting to know you with honorable intent,” not “let’s blur every line and call it complicated.”

It looks like deleting the thing that keeps dragging you into sin.

It looks like telling the truth faster.

It looks like praying when you would rather numb out.

It looks like serving when nobody sees.

It looks like becoming useful.

Here is the hard truth: God is not impressed by a man who talks about leadership but cannot lead his own appetites. He is not impressed by a man who wants a submissive wife but will not submit to Christ. He is not impressed by a man who wants respect but refuses responsibility.

But here is the good news: God builds men out of sinners.

Not polished sinners. Real ones.

The kind who have lusted, lied, wasted time, chased approval, worshiped comfort, and hated themselves afterward.

Christ does not call you to stay there. He calls you to get up, repent, and follow him with your whole life.

A righteous man in 2026 is not sinless.

He is done making excuses.

He belongs to Christ, he tells the truth, he kills what is killing him, he builds what will bless others, and he walks with God when nobody is clapping.